main/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2013-11-27 13:39:32'), ('44', 'UKY-HIC', 'HIC', 'Hymenoptera Institute Collection', 'a8a78602-8293-4636-943a-aa4e7a91dfe7', null, '19', 'The Hymenoptera Institute Collection is a collection of largely parasitic Hymenoptera housed in Michael Sharkey’s Lab in the Entomology Department (Agricultural Science Center North) at the University of Kentucky. The museum houses over 350 drawers of Hymenoptera focusing on Braconidae, with the primary focus on the braconid subfamily Agathidinae. The braconid collection is of world-scope, having received samples from all continents except Antarctica and is primarily used to describe new species and conduct molecular phylogenetics studies. Major recent projects include the Thailand Biodiversity Project (TIGER), the Columbia Biodiversity Project, and the Hymatol Project (phylogeny of Hymenoptera). More information can be found at the Sharkey Lab webpage: http://sharkeylab.org/sharkeylab/sharkeyProjects.php', 'http://sharkeylab.org/sharkeylab/sharkeyProjects.html', null, 'Eric Chapman', 'ericgchapman@gmail.com', '38.047010', '-84.504090', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/uky.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'a8a78602-8293-4636-943a-aa4e7a91dfe7', 'cc5a12d8-4858-4a8f-a1c8-9a0d253396bb', 'symbiotaUUID', 'University of Kentucky', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'not-for-profit use only', null, '2014-01-06 15:10:39'), ('45', 'AMNH', 'BEE', 'North American Bee Collections', 'fe016d18-13a3-4b7d-a66e-9746cc6158a2', null, null, 'This collection is a snapshot of two projects. The first project is collections data from the Tri-Trophic Interactions ADBC Thematic Collections Network at the American Museum of Natural History http://tcn.amnh.org/. The second collection consists of data from a bee PBI project. Data for both of these projects are being served on SCAN to provide added value to SCAN users. Although the American Museum of Natural History served as the lead institution for both of these projects, a number of institutions have collaborated in the digitization. Please download data-sets from the iDigBio portal , which serves as the primary portal for these data-sets.', 'https://www.idigbio.org/portal/recordsets/8919571f-205a-4aed-b9f2-96ccd0108e4c', null, 'John S. Ascher', 'dbsajs@nus.edu.sg', null, null, null, 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', 'fe016d18-13a3-4b7d-a66e-9746cc6158a2', 'ea505c28-28c0-431a-b78e-01c6bdb20eab', 'occurrenceId', 'SCAN', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'CC BY-NC (Attribution-Non-Commercial)', null, '2014-03-16 14:06:59'), ('47', 'IDIGBIO', 'IDIGBIO', 'iDigBio Extract', 'cb969666-dad7-4780-8dd6-c12ee9fb787d', null, null, 'These data are an extract of north american arthropod records from the collections at iDigBio. This extract is a snapshot and was collected in March 2014.', null, null, 'Neil Cobb', 'neil.cobb@nau.edu', null, null, null, 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', 'cb969666-dad7-4780-8dd6-c12ee9fb787d', '228adc04-83fa-4162-b35a-7dfc54e2daf7', null, 'SCAN', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'CC BY-NC (Attribution-Non-Commercial)', null, '2014-03-18 15:38:48'), ('49', 'UAQ', 'UAQE', 'Colección Zoológica de la Universidad Autónoma de Querétaro', '7a6d98a0-9e48-4035-b3fb-0a3f4a2c04d4', null, null, 'TBA.', null, null, 'Dr. Robert W. Jones', 'rjones@uaq.mx', '20.700960', '-100.443840', null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '7a6d98a0-9e48-4035-b3fb-0a3f4a2c04d4', '66c34196-322c-48a0-becd-464b98a136f9', 'symbiotaUUID', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2014-04-23 13:53:31'), ('50', 'UHIM', 'UHIM', 'University of Hawaii Insect Museum', '0fc43ef4-018d-479a-a633-3653718ec766', null, '22', 'The University of Hawaii Insect Museum (UHIM) is the second largest collection of insects in the state of Hawaii and ranks among the biggest collections in the world for Hawaiian insect holdings. The collection dates to 1908, and as such houses an important record of changes in arthropod biodiversity over time, including the extinction and introduction of species. The museum houses over 250,000 specimens, with strengths in endemic Diptera and Lepidoptera. The UHIM also serves as a center for research and education about biodiversity and systematics for the University of Hawaii system.', 'http://www.ctahr.hawaii.edu/insectmuseum/', null, 'Dan Rubinoff', 'rubinoff@hawaii.edu', '21.301617', '-157.816567', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/Manoa-seal.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '0fc43ef4-018d-479a-a633-3653718ec766', '2c9e24d2-0a92-445e-a8cc-e7b8fab7cf6a', null, 'University of Hawaii Insect Museum', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'not-for-profit use only', null, '2014-04-28 15:02:59'), ('51', 'TAMU', 'TAMU-TTI', 'Tri-Trophic Interactions - Texas A&M', '7c429a87-93ff-406a-9c33-7a6ed387d3c9', null, '6', 'These data represent the segment of the Tri-Trophic Interactions Project housed at Texas A&M University.', 'http://insects.tamu.edu/tamuinsectcollection/', null, 'Dr. John D. Oswald', 'j-oswald@tamu.edu', '30.611190', '-96.348140', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/atm.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '7c429a87-93ff-406a-9c33-7a6ed387d3c9', 'ec9eee86-f368-4a72-8f97-8d653bd50488', null, 'Texas A&M University', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'Not-for-profit use only', null, '2014-05-19 17:15:09'), ('53', 'DUGWAY', 'DUG-ENT', 'Dugway Proving Ground Natural History Collection', null, null, '23', 'The Dugway Proving Ground Natural History Collection houses more than 1,100 specimens of plants, insects, spiders, amphibians, reptiles, birds and mammals collected primarily from the U.S. Army Dugway Proving Ground but also include some areas just outside the installation within Tooele County. The collection is used in support of the Army Mission on the West Desert of Utah, in scientific research, education and outreach efforts. One objective of this collection is to ensure preservation of species of concern and document localities and habitats for management of sensitive and/or rare species mandated by the endangered species act.', 'http://www.dugway.army.mil/', null, 'Robert Delph', 'Robert.Delph@nau.edu', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/dugway.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'b192dbaf-eae2-4613-a48c-5e9d0c4cca5c', 'fbf013a4-9104-4132-b851-899fdd00d085', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Dugway Proving Ground Natural History Collection', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'CC BY-NC', null, '2014-09-11 12:00:39'), ('54', 'UTC', 'UTCI', 'University of Tennessee at Chattanooga', null, null, '38', 'The University of Tennessee at Chattanooga Insect collection started in 1970 with Dr. Charles Nelson, a Plecoptera expert. For several years it grew into an extensive teaching collection with representative of most insect families found in the Southeastern USA. In 2008, Dr. Stylianos Chatzimanolis initiated the Coleoptera collection, which is fully curated and databased. The main focus of the Coleoptera collection is the Southeastern USA but several other countries are represented. We welcome visitors and loan requests; please contact Stylianos Chatzimanolis at the email address below or at @schatzimanolis.', 'http://www.utc.edu/biology-geology-environmental-science/facilities/facilities.php', null, 'Stylianos Chatzimanolis', 'stylianos-chatzimanolis@utc.edu', '35.047730', '-85.296380', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/utc.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'a9451a2e-c7ab-45be-bbd5-75bee864d055', '4c82d59d-5d70-4d56-a620-4067b64a728e', 'symbiotaUUID', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2014-11-17 19:13:24'), ('55', 'OSU', 'OSU', 'Ohio State C.A. Triplehorn Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'This collection is comprised of an extract of specimen records from the Ohio State C.A. Triplehorn Insect Collection. These records are also included in the Triplehorn Museum\'s GBIF feed. Further aggregation is not recommended.', 'wasps.osu.edu', null, 'Norman F. Johnson', 'johnson.2@osu.edu', '39.997100', '-83.043982', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/OSU.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'b4da3ef0-06c9-471b-ad36-9e964c6a66c6', '58839b52-9a5c-436f-98c3-8b038639d3f2', 'occurrenceId', 'Ohio State University', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2014-11-26 11:14:52'), ('56', 'UGCA', 'GMNH', 'University of Georgia Collection of Arthropods', null, null, '24', 'The University of Georgia Collection of Arthropods (UGCA) serves as the official state repository of insects and other non-marine arthropods. The Collection is part of the UGA Department of Entomology and the Georgia Museum of Natural History (GMNH). The UGCA includes approximately 2,000,000 pinned specimens. In addition the collection houses significant alcohol-preserved and slide-mounted collections. Approximately 60% of the holdings are from the southeastern United States as is consistent with our mission to serve as the primary systematics reference for the state. More than 70% of that regional material is identified to the species level.', 'http://www.ugca.uga.edu/index.html', null, 'Joseph V. McHugh', 'mchugh.jv@gmail.com', '33.945070', '-83.372370', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/UGCA_logo_sm.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'e7bcca50-5afb-4728-a5c4-014551fe50a0', '9a77c92c-0700-47b0-ac6c-4792bbe7a6e9', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Georgia Museum of Natural History', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, 'Material is available via loans to researchers around the world and for in-house use.', null, '2015-01-16 11:20:59'), ('57', 'DBG', 'DBGA', 'Denver Botanic Gardens Collection of Arthropods', null, null, '25', 'The Denver Botanic Gardens Collection of Arthropods (DBGA) is small collection with a research focus on horticultural pests and beneficial insects. Specimen and observation data is primarily collected from managed gardens and agricultural areas in the Colorado Front Range. The collection also contains specimens from other areas in the Southern Rocky Mountain Region, particularly sites with ongoing research projects organized by the Denver Botanic Gardens. Collections are primarily made by volunteers and identifications are often only to family level.', 'http://www.botanicgardens.org/science-research/our-collections', null, 'Rick Levy', 'Richard.Levy@botanicgardens.org', '39.732540', '-104.960980', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/DBG-logo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '05db5b76-3037-46db-ba55-79607d9fc050', '627c87f3-9af9-4bf2-982b-02d61326ffd6', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Denver Botanic Gardens', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, '0', null, null, null, '2015-01-27 13:53:34'), ('58', 'PU', 'PERC', 'The Purdue Entomological Research Collection', null, null, null, 'The Purdue Entomological Research Collection (PERC) is an integral part of the Department of Entomology at Purdue University. Specimens housed in the collection are the basis for research in systematic entomology at Purdue and by specialists worldwide. The PERC also serves as a reference to facilitate the accurate and timely identification of insects for extension and teaching needs. Approximately 2 million specimens are held, representing more than 140,000 species. This includes mainly dry-mounted pinned material as well as many specimens stored in liquid preservative or mounted on slides.', 'http://www.entm.purdue.edu/PERC/', null, 'Dr. Jennifer M. Zaspel', 'jzaspel@purdue.edu', '40.423580', '-86.916930', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/PERC_Logo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '61cff121-261e-4eff-a186-a377f91aa027', '32923fe5-c6ab-4ff8-b825-d2c8d269434b', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Purdue University, Department of Entomology', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-02 19:20:19'), ('59', 'UAM', 'UAM_ENT', 'UAM Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'This collection is comprised of an extract of specimen records from the University of Alaska Museum Entomology Collection. These records are also included in the UAM iDigBio feed. If further aggregation is desired please contact the curator of the University of Alaska Museum Insect Collection to ask permission to aggregate data from their source IPT instance.', 'http://www.uaf.edu/museum/collections/ento/', null, 'Dr. Derek Sikes', 'dssikes@alaska.edu', '64.856090', '-147.831000', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/UAM.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '8cafaa53-4c65-4155-ae9c-13e51dabe170', '9089bd81-526d-4a50-a8c9-48665ea23e4c', null, 'University of Alaska Museum', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-03 09:55:15'), ('60', 'YPM', 'ENT', 'Yale Peabody Museum, Entomology Division', null, null, null, 'This collection is comprised of an extract of specimen records from the Yale University Peabody Museum Entomology Division. These records are also included in the Peabody Museum\'s iDigBio feed. Further aggregation is not recommended.”', 'http://peabody.yale.edu/', null, 'Dr. Lawrence Gall', 'lawrence.gall@yale.edu', '41.310820', '-72.958060', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/yale.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'eebda952-05ec-474e-833e-1a2085294977', '904ace1e-e1c5-405d-8b32-560a15e74b30', null, 'Yale University', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-03 10:14:11'), ('61', 'KU', 'SEMC', 'University of Kansas Natural History Museum Entomology Division', null, null, null, 'This collection is comprised of an extract of specimen records from the University of Kansas Natural History Museum Entomology Division. These records are also included in the KU Natural History Museum iDigBio feed. Further aggregation is not recommended.', 'http://entomology.biodiversity.ku.edu/entomology', null, 'Dr. Zack Falin', 'ksem@ku.edu', '38.954770', '-95.256060', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/ku.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'c45886f1-3524-42f4-a113-4e4e193505a8', '0c3e84b8-a8c1-4b3b-a27b-127ad2f8a144', null, 'The University of Kansas Natural History Museum', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-03 10:33:37'), ('62', 'CAS', 'ANTWEB', 'AntWeb', null, null, '34', 'This collection is comprised of an extract of specimen records from AntWeb.org. AntWeb is the world\'s largest online database of images, specimen records, and natural history information on ants. It is community driven and open to contribution from anyone with specimen records, natural history comments, or images. These records are also included in the AntWeb\'s iDigBio feed. Further aggregation is not recommended.', 'http://antweb.org/', null, 'Dr. Brian Fisher', 'bfisher@calacademy.org', '37.769120', '-122.473440', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/calacademy.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'dc646193-9811-40ce-872a-f005f7dc059a', 'a89f3d54-250f-43a4-b3bb-d9c5a3d17e95', null, 'The California Academy of Sciences - AntWeb.org', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-03 11:27:16'), ('63', 'ASU', 'CAPART', 'LTER Central Arizona Phoenix Arthropod Collection', null, null, null, 'Arthropod collection maintained by the CAP-LTER project. In the rapidly growing Phoenix metropolitan region, long-term monitoring allows scientists to monitor changes as urbanization takes place in urban fringe areas and as density increases in already urbanized areas.', 'https://caplter.asu.edu/', null, 'Annie Deutsch', 'aedeutsch@asu.edu', '33.420030', '-111.933000', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/CAPLTER.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '4231ad72-781c-4347-88cd-ff13e2f77387', '643d62e5-1da6-4f74-9329-d02ede875e54', 'symbiotaUUID', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-03 13:23:41'), ('64', 'SDSU', 'TAC', 'SDSU Terrestrial Arthropods Collection', null, null, '32', 'The SDSU Terrestrial Arthropods Collection includes an estimated 50,000 specimens of pinned insects, a slide-mount collection, and many terrestrial arthropods (e.g., insects, arachnids, myriapods) preserved in ethanol. Most of these specimens were collected in southern California and adjacent regions (e.g., Arizona, Baja California Mexico). The collection holdings in Arachnida, Orthoptera, Lepidoptera, and Coleoptera are particularly strong. The collection is an important resource for both the teaching and research missions of the Department of Biology at SDSU, with a synoptic collection of local insects kept specifically for this purpose.', 'http://www.sci.sdsu.edu/collections/terrestrialarthropods.htm', null, 'Dr. Marshal Hedin', 'mhedin@mail.sdsu.edu', '32.777350', '-117.071930', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/SDSU_TAC_logo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '1', 'c425cbc1-db60-4f45-be76-95358932734c', '10e6d175-1178-4a04-8aa1-903e59b1cd4f', 'symbiotaUUID', 'SDSU Terrestrial Arthropods Collection', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-02-12 17:34:00'), ('65', 'GBIF', 'GBIF_LOC', 'GBIF Extract with Location Data', null, null, null, 'This collection is an extract of all GBIF arthropod records with location data extracted on 2 March 2015. No further aggregation is recommended.', 'http://nau.edu/Merriam-Powell/Biodiversity-Center/Museum-of-Arthropod-Biodiversity/', null, 'Neil Cobb', 'neil.cobb@nau.edu', '35.192680', '-111.652940', null, 'Observations', 'Aggregate', '0', '8665f77a-4f21-4c4d-8fd2-4811d31e6225', '1552b294-1416-4c19-80b3-f7d6100b1c53', null, 'Northern Arizona University', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-03-02 11:08:57'), ('66', 'GBIF', 'GBIF_NOLOC', 'GBIF Extract without Location Information', null, null, null, 'This collection is an extract of all GBIF arthropod records without location data extracted on 2 March 2015. We have harvested this data from GBIF to provide added value to our own spider records. Please download these records from GBIF.', 'http://nau.edu/Merriam-Powell/Biodiversity-Center/Museum-of-Arthropod-Biodiversity/', null, 'GBIF', 'GBIF website', '35.192290', '-111.652890', null, 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', '7ffe9f61-4b30-4f52-9f05-8a7b2cacb136', 'e729578a-6494-4f0d-bb8d-1477d1fdede7', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-03-02 11:11:46'), ('67', 'WWU', 'WWUC', 'Western Washington University Insect Collection', null, null, '33', 'The Western Washington University Insect Collection houses approximately 50,000 insect specimens. Our geographic area of focus is the northwestern portion of the contiguous United States. Most of our specimens are from the northwestern portion of Washington State, an area that is poorly represented in other collections in the region. The collection is the largest publicly-held insect collection within a 100 mile radius centered on Seattle.  ', 'http://pnwmoths.biol.wwu.edu/', null, 'Merrill Peterson', 'Merrill.Peterson@wwu.edu', '48.730000', '-122.490000', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/WWUlogo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'be43e4da-bd95-4cdb-a590-3129a4cef884', '82602fb4-982d-481e-82fa-1e9ecb4773a8', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Western Washington University', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'not-for-profit use only', null, '2015-04-03 15:58:37'), ('68', 'CAS', 'ENT', 'California Academy of Sciences Entomology', null, null, '34', 'Through active fieldwork, laboratory research, and management our 10 million specimens, we advance knowledge about Earth\'s insects and arachnids — taxonomic groups vital to healthy ecosystems. These digitized occurrence records are here for you! Enjoy!', 'http://www.calacademy.org/scientists/entomology', null, 'Anne Barber', 'abarber@calacademy.org', '37.769530', '-122.466190', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/calacademy.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '1beb0a27-4138-489c-9694-1b3f9f4e57cf', 'de8a02d3-d863-460a-98f6-d3a68b291ce0', 'catalogNumber', 'California Academy of Sciences', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-04-08 16:43:45'), ('69', 'UD', 'UDCC', 'University of Delaware Insect Research Collection', null, null, null, 'The University of Delaware Insect Research Collection was founded with the creation of the Agricultural Research Station at Delaware College (now University of Delaware) in the 1880’s, and became associated with the Department of Entomology when the Department was founded in 1925. It is a scientific research collection historically focused on the insects and other arthropods of Delaware (or more broadly, the Delmarva Peninsula, which comprise about 75% of the collection), especially those of agroeconomic importance. However, in recent years, the collection has sought to incorporated specimens from a much broader geographic spectrum. The collection consists of approximately 350,000 pinned specimens, plus several thousand specimens in alcohol and a few hundred on slides. Collection strengths from past researchers or students include biting flies, aquatic insects (esp. Bob Lake’s Trichoptera and Plecoptera, plus Hydrophilidae from Andrew Short), Formicidae, and bees. Recent years have resulted in a great expansion of the Hemiptera collection, in particular the Auchenorrhyncha, of which some 40,000 specimens have been digitized as part of the Tri-Trophic Hemiptera TCH supported by NSF. Further digitization projects are actively sought, particularly if they involve the active participation of UD undergraduate students.', 'http://ag.udel.edu/research/planthoppers/index.html', null, 'Charles Bartlett', 'Bartlett@udel.edu', '39.665250', '-75.750067', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/udirc.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '303067f9-527d-458e-81ea-0894c44b9e23', 'aef20c67-db21-4acd-b59c-69101d01f0a2', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Charles Bartlett', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'Not for Profit', null, '2015-04-16 17:25:55'), ('70', 'FLMNH', 'MGCL', 'Florida Museum of Natural History, McGuire Center for Lepidoptera and Biodiversity', null, null, '36', 'The Florida Museum of Natural History’s McGuire Center for Lepidoptera and Biodiversity, on the University of Florida campus in Gainesville, Florida, has become one of the world’s largest institutions for research on butterflies and moths, and an important research facility for insect science. The facility was constructed by combining the staff and merging the Lepidoptera holdings from the Allyn Museum of Entomology, the Florida State Collection of Arthropods and other University of Florida collections, and now may include over ten million specimens from all over the world, rivaling some of the largest Lepidoptera research collections globally. The facility includes a team of domestic and international researchers studying many areas of lepidopterology, including behavior, biodiversity, biogeography, ecology, genomics, physiology, systematics and taxonomy.', 'www.flmnh.ufl.edu/mcguire', null, 'Akito Kawahara', 'kawahara@flmnh.ufl.edu', null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '32180c92-8d89-4e4a-8af5-6749f47ea299', 'c3d94c44-22c8-4201-803c-5b6ffb4860d2', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Florida Museum of Natural History, McGuire Center', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-05-01 13:36:25'), ('71', 'ANSP', 'ANSP', 'Academy of Natural Sciences, Entomology Collection', null, null, null, 'The collection contains ca. 3.5 million insects and non-insect arthropods and over 106,000 species (more than 2/3 of these are curated/labeled, and the remainder are unsorted/undetermined and bulk samples). It is the oldest insect collection in the Americas, dating back to the early 19th Century, including the Peale Butterfly & Moth Collection. The type collection is substantial, with over 13,000 specimens dating to the origins of American Entomology. The collection’s unique strength is Orthoptera and allied orders (ca. 1 million specimens). For Orthoptera, this is one of the three largest collections in the world, and the most complete for New World taxa. The core of the Orthoptera collection was formed by J.A.G. Rehn & M. Hebard. Collections of other great orthopterists have been deposited at ANSP. These include Hancock (Tetrigidae), Otte (Acrididae, Gryllidae), Bruner, and Scudder. The Orthoptera collection contains ca. 3000 primary types. There are substantial holdings in non-orthopteroid orders as well. The collections of Cresson (Hymenoptera, Diptera), Cresson Jr. (Diptera), Roback (Chironomidae), Fee (Syrphidae), Gelhaus (Tipulidae), Fox, Norton, Pate, Viereck, Bassett, Cockerell, Blake (Hymenoptera), Braun, Clemens, Darlington, and Grote (Lepidoptera), Poey (Cuban entomofauna), Calvert (Odonata) and Allen (Diplura, Protura) are among the more notable components. The alcohol collection is very strong for Nearctic aquatic insects resulting from decades of river surveys. The entomofauna of the New Jersey Pine Barrens is well represented, and a separate synoptic collection from the Parker Preserve (Burlington Co., NJ) is searchable online [see http://symbiont.ansp.org/portal/index.php ]. Non-insect arthropods include Araneae, Diplopoda, Chilopoda, Scorpiones and Solifugae. An associated collection of sound recordings of Orthoptera forms part of the research collection. [For a collection index, see http://symbiont.ansp.org/entomology ].', 'http://www.ansp.org', null, 'Jason Weintraub', 'weintraub@ansp.org', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/drexel.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'af7140c3-4aa2-41ac-b3e9-4c7415b3ce90', 'e146a2d9-0717-4adf-a850-549440180a5d', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Academy of Natural Sciences', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, '0', null, 'CC BY-NC (Attribution-Non-Commercial)', null, '2015-05-08 15:58:58'), ('73', 'MPM', 'MPM IZ', 'Milwaukee Public Museum, Invertebrate Zoology-Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'The Milwaukee Public Museum Invertebrate Zoology Collection numbers about 800,000 specimens of which 70% are insects and 30% are other invertebrate groups encompassing a broad diversity of animals (52 zoological classes.) Lepidoptera and Coleoptera comprise the largest portions of the insect collections, and Mollusca and Crustacea the largest collections of other invertebrates. Special insect collections include the Type Collection (about 60 holotypes and 55 syntypes) of various orders, tropical Lepidoptera and gynandromorphs from James R. Neidhoefer, a worldwide collection of Sphingidae from William E. Sieker, the Albert Schwartz collection of West Indies Lepidoptera, determined Costa Rican cacao-pollinating midges (Ceratopogonidae and Cecidomyiidae) from Allen M. Young’s research. Other significant invertebrate collections include a comprehensive survey of WI crayfishes made by the WI Department of Natural Resources, Horton H. Hobbs III and Joan P. Jass, the Harold Mathiak collection of WI freshwater unionids, and the WI arachnid collection, including the historically important George W. and Elizabeth G. Peckham Collection of jumping spiders. A more detailed description is available at http://www.mpm.edu/research-collections/invertebrate-zoology/collections-overview. For further information or loans, please contact Collection Manager Julia Colby (colby@mpm.edu).', 'http://www.mpm.edu', null, 'Julia Colby (Collection Manager)', 'colby@mpm.edu', '43.040707', '-87.921338', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/mpm_logo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '267fcb1b-0323-4f91-b6bd-e61a8cf40d83', '78784c3d-4e00-46e5-a324-ae29066756aa', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Milwaukee Public Museum', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, 'Milwaukee Public Museum', null, '2015-06-02 18:07:11');
INSERT INTO `omcollections` VALUES ('74', 'USNM', 'USNMENT', 'United States National Museum, Entomology Collections', null, null, null, 'The USNM Entomology Collection is one of the largest insect collections in the World. The collection contains over 300,000 species representing approximately 60% of known insect families. With approximately 35 million specimens, including 100,000 holotypes and hundreds of additional paratypes and other secondary types, in more than 232,000 drawers in 5200 cabinets, 33,000 jars or vials, and 50,000 slides from locations worldwide, the collection is strongest in coverage for Nearctic and Neotropical regions. Specimens from the Old World are also well represented, especially Sri Lanka, Philippines, and Papua New Guinea. Particular strengths include mosquitoes, wasps, beetles, butterflies and moths and flies. The collection of Coleoptera at USNM is one of the world’s largest, consisting of more than 10 million specimens, including over 20,000 primary types. The nucleus of the National Collection was formed in 1881 with the transfer of the general collection of the U.S. Department of Agriculture to the National Museum of Natural History. Notable collection acquisitions and donations have significantly enhanced the National Coleoptera Collection. The majority of the collection is housed at the Smithsonian Institution’s National Museum of Natural History in Washington, DC, other groups are held at the USDA’s Agricultural Research Center in Beltsville, Maryland and the Smithsonian Institution’s Museum Support Center in Suitland, Maryland. The Department of Entomology includes research scientists and museum specialists from the Smithsonian Institution, U.S.D.A. Systematic Entomology Lab and Walter Reed Biosystematics Unit of the Department of Defense.', 'http://entomology.si.edu/default.html', null, 'M. Lourdes Chamorro', 'Lourdes.Chamorro@ars.usda.gov', '38.891266', '-77.026065', 'http://www.wornthrough.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/Smithsonian-Logo.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '1', '043bee8b-d64c-4136-a7c1-f79af60d4a13', 'a627db7d-e777-43c0-b0ef-2edbecab84c8', 'symbiotaUUID', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-06-20 01:31:39'), ('75', 'VPI', 'VTEC', 'Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'The Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University Insect Collection is the oldest and largest entomological collection in Virginia. Founded in 1888 by W.B. Alwood at the university’s first experimental station with just a few insects collected from his apple orchards, the collection now composes more than 500,000 specimens. The collection contains many entomological treasures like American Burying Beetles collected from Blacksburg in 1889 (now extinct from the state), colorful Malaysian butterflies, a herbarium of plant pests, and an extensive slide collection of 50,000 soil mites. In addition to pinned dried specimens, the VTEC holds an alcohol collection of aquatic insects and Appalachian millipedes.', 'http://collection.ento.vt.edu/', null, 'Paul Marek', 'pmarek@vt.edu', '37.224850', '-80.423840', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/VT.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'cbb0e637-c014-4f09-99a1-37d1bbfdfb70', 'f6b07c0a-8293-477b-822f-0f8ab9de01b7', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Virginia Tech, Department of Entomology', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-06-25 17:29:35'), ('76', 'MSU', 'MSUC', 'The Albert J. Cook Arthropod Research Collection', null, null, null, 'In 1867, Professor Albert J. Cook started the ARC and it currently houses ~ 1.5 million specimens mounted on pins, slides or stored in alcohol representing ~35,000 species. A significant portion of the collection represents the insect diversity Michigan and the Great Lakes Region. Other significant collections represent the world-wide arthropod fauna for select taxa, e.g., Lepidoptera and Scolytinae. Researchers in systematics, agriculture, natural resources, urban insect management, to extension personnel and to the general public use these specimens. Please direct inquiries to Anthony Cognato, Director or Gary Parsons, Manager (parsonsg@cns.msu.edu).', 'http://www.arc.ent.msu.edu/', null, 'Anthony Cognato', 'cognato@msu.edu', '42.731063', '-84.477324', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/msu.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '15cdb244-b82d-4798-af5e-ef7bc138f233', '07e5d45e-e845-4e7a-aa6f-1be38fe2d4d3', 'symbiotaUUID', 'Department of Entomology, MSU', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-07-02 17:18:58'), ('78', 'UCD', 'BMEC', 'R. M.Bohart Museum of Entomology', null, null, null, 'The Bohart Museum’s mission is to serve the research community, support campus teaching, provide science educational outreach for the public, and to provide diagnostic and information services. The museum houses the seventh largest insect collection in North America. The museum specializes in the unique insect fauna of California, both native and exotic species. Current holdings of nearly 8 million specimens include a wide range of terrestrial invertebrates, specializing in arthropods (insects, millipedes, centipedes, scorpions, mites, ticks, and spiders), crustaceans (pill and sow bugs, fairy and tadpole shrimp), and tardigrade water bears. The largest collections are of the Lepidoptera, Hymenoptera, Coleoptera, Acarina and Tardigrada. The collections are worldwide in scope, with the Americas, south Asia and Australia particularly well-represented. The museum is also the home of the California Insect Survey and sponsors research on the California fauna.', 'http://Bohart.ucdavis.edu', null, 'Lynn S. Kimsey', 'lskimsey@ucdavis.edu', '38.535344', '-121.752310', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/bohart.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '79aa23b2-db5f-4b44-9484-e8af67d3db86', '20b1fc31-ba6d-4287-bb5d-2015215a5dc6', 'symbiotaUUID', 'University of California', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'Not-for-profit use, except by contract', null, '2015-07-09 12:32:26'), ('79', 'MIN', 'UMSP', 'University of Minnesota Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'The University of Minnesota Insect Collection’s mission is to explore, describe, and preserve representative specimens of Earth’s remarkable diversity of insects and to make these specimens available to the global community for research and education. Contributions to the collection began in 1879 with specimens of insects and spiders from the North Shore of Lake Superior. During the last 135 years, the collection’s holdings have grown from a regional collection of 3,000 specimens to a major national and international resource of more than 3.8 million specimens. The collection is one of the largest university-affiliated insect collections in North America. Enhancing the collection’s status are 6 resident systematists, computerized inventory management and specimen databases, the large and historically important affiliated University of Minnesota Natural Resources Library, and a molecular systematics laboratory. Invertnet, a collaborative effort among major Midwestern universities coordinated by the University of Illinois and funded by the National Science Foundation, is currently underway to digitize the collection’s specimen holdings. Research projects associated with the collection have broad taxonomic and geographic scope. Faculty and graduate student research focuses on both aquatic and terrestrial insect groups and includes taxonomic, phylogenetic, and applied questions. The collection is the mainstay of graduate training is systematic entomology at the University of Minnesota.', 'http://insectcollection.umn.edu/', 'images/collicons/UM_logo.png', 'Robin Elizabeth Thomson', 'thom1514@umn.edu', '44.988025', '-93.183665', null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'ad7e4ae3-ab29-41f0-a66a-2f0e4756b2c1', '79eb3961-7d6e-4f38-adb6-20c516166241', null, 'Regents of the University of Minnesota', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-07-16 18:56:03'), ('80', 'KSU', 'MEPAR', 'K-State Museum of Entomological and Prairie Arthropod Research', null, null, null, 'The Kansas State University Museum of Entomological and Prairie Arthropod Research (KSU-MEPAR) is nearly as old as Kansas State University itself, having been started in 1879 by E. A. Popenoe, the first full-time entomologist employed at the Kansas State College. The collection has grown considerably since that time and is estimated to contain approximately 300,000 specimens. The type collection includes 52 holotypes, and 2,214 paratype specimens representing 668 species. The majority of the specimens are from the midwestern states and the western U.S. Many of the specimens were collected from local and regional prairies between 1880 and 1920, providing valuable historical specimens and records of the fauna before the land succumbed to farming and ranching. A significant amount of Neotropical, and some Old World, specimens are also present. The primary purposes of the museum are to collect, preserve, and maintain a research collection of insects and other arthropods, and their associated information, that represent the natural history of Kansas and the prairie region; to study and interpret this information; to make the specimens and other information available for study by researchers; and to use the museum as a resource of information through publications, exhibits, displays, and other informative outreach activities.', 'http://entomology.k-state.edu/department-info/facilities/insect-museum/', null, 'Gregory Zolnerowich', 'gregz@ksu.edu', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/k-state.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '190d5a14-8148-4a50-bfd8-5323fae78671', '953786a9-9209-4fbb-a2db-e45505a917ff', 'catalogNumber', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-07-28 15:22:07'), ('81', 'UNR', 'ENTO', 'University of Nevada, Reno, Museum of Natural History, Entomology Research Collection', null, null, null, 'Reared specimens associated with interaction diversity datasets from across the Americas. Supplemented with adult collections. In addition to homepage please visit www.caterpillars.org', 'http://wolfweb.unr.edu/~ophis/Feldman_Lab/Museum.html', null, 'Lee Dyer', 'ldyer@unr.edu', '39.537723', '-119.812115', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/MuseumofNaturalHistorySmall.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '046eddff-cf84-40f7-979b-e6b7b42d718c', '466ff84e-cc5d-47bf-8b5a-0cee059066b5', null, 'University of Nevada, Reno, Museum of Natural History', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-08-09 23:51:35'), ('82', 'OMNH', 'RINVRT', 'The Sam Noble Museum Department of Recent Invertebrates', null, null, null, 'The Collection of Recent Invertebrates, with its >500,000 specimens, presents a nice sampling of invertebrate diversity. Focus of the collection is on Oklahoma invertebrates, but it also contains specimens from more than 100 countries and territories. We are unique among invertebrate collections by pursuing cataloging of all of our specimens. Data is also served to iDigBio under SNOMNH IPT - Recent invertebrates https://www.idigbio.org/portal/recordsets/2e6b6643-ebc7-4a80-a7ea-f4dd7b9c42e7', 'http://samnoblemuseum.ou.edu/collections-and-research/recent-invertebrates/', null, 'Katrina Menard', 'Kmenard@ou.edu', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/ou.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '49a4c697-e495-4654-83e5-c1e072eebfee', 'e3a43b5f-8fbb-4f64-945d-7f7f3076d471', null, 'The University of Oklahoma', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-08-24 09:56:20'), ('83', 'MSU', 'MEM', 'The Mississippi Entomological Museum', null, null, null, 'The Mississippi Entomological Museum (MEM) is located in the Clay Lyle Entomology Building at Mississippi State University. The MEM initiated the Mississippi Arthropod Survey in 1982 and the Midsouth Arthropod Survey in 1990, with the latter emphasizing arthropods in unique and threatened habitats in Mississippi, Alabama, and Louisiana. During the past ten years faunistic research has extended to all southeastern states as well as southwestern U.S., especially Arizona. The museum serves as a screening and identification center for USDA-APHIS surveys for exotic species in six states. The museum currently has six full time staff, including three permanent on state funding concentrating on faunistics/systematics of moths, ants, and wood boring beetles and three on cooperative agreements working on grasshoppers, calliphorids, and ants. In addition the staff includes two graduate students and 10-12d undergraduate students and intermittent workers. Holdings of the museum now include more than one million labeled specimens. Data management: The museum uses the Silver Collection web portal for displaying data for 80,000 specimens, including all microlepidoptera at: http://www.mississippientomologicalmuseum.org.msstate.edu/collection/mem/. Hemiptera data have been captured for the -Trophic Interactions ADBC Thematic Collections Network at the American Museum of Natural History http://tcn.amnh.org/.', 'http://mississippientomologicalmuseum.org.msstate.edu/', null, 'Richard Brown', 'RBrown@entomology.msstate.edu', null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '00879411-4d69-405c-ac8a-e366dff0570c', 'bd7a97e7-e156-4ae9-9d7a-974fbe2b5ad0', null, 'Mississippi State University', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-08-24 10:00:37'), ('84', 'UAM', 'UASM', 'University of Alberta Museums Entomology Collection (UASM)', null, null, null, 'The E. H. Strickland Entomological Museum houses approximately one million specimens. The research collection includes principally Nearctic insects, representing most orders and the major families thereof. The beetle family Carabidae is especially well represented: included are about 400,000 specimens mainly from the Nearctic region, but with an important Neotropical component, and fewer taxa from the remaining biogeographic regions of the world. The moths and butterflies, order Lepidoptera, with over 65,000 specimens, about half of which are from Alberta localities, are another group of major interest.', 'http://www.biology.museums.ualberta.ca/EHStricklandEntomologicalMuseum.aspx', null, 'Dr. Felix Sperling', 'felix.sperling@ualberta.ca', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/alberta.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '8f56ab7d-7115-4a54-a3f4-034a722f90c8', '670d602f-0af2-42b8-af1f-c7d8a4970b5b', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-08-26 18:19:06'), ('85', 'OSU', 'OSAC', 'Oregon State Arthropod Collection', null, null, null, 'The OSAC is a research collection of approximately 3 million non-marine arthropod and molluscan specimens. Strengths are Coleoptera, Hymenoptera, Lepidoptera, Hemiptera and Acari. The fauna of the Pacific Northwest is particularly well represented, but the collection is global in scope. The collection includes both primary and secondary types. More information can be found on their website: http:osac.oregonstate.edu.', 'http://osac.oregonstate.edu', null, 'Christopher Marshall', 'Christopher.Marshall@oregonstate.edu', '44.567000', '-123.281800', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/oregonstate.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '03cc8826-c198-496a-8548-fb451f1b0262', '88d9c44a-d11d-4d07-bdb1-7e016647f613', null, 'Oregon State University', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-08-27 19:47:46'), ('88', 'CU', 'CUAC', 'Clemson University Arthropod Collection', null, null, null, 'The Clemson University Arthropod Collection (CUAC) supports the teaching, research, and extension activities of the University. The Collection consists of approximately 1.3 million specimens from Classes Insecta, Arachnida, Branchipoda, Copepoda, Diplopoda, and Chilopoda. The wet, alcohol-preserved collection is exceptionally rich, with over 1,000,000 specimens, nearly half of which are Trichoptera, or caddisflies, resulting from 40 years of work by Director Emeritus Dr. John Morse. The pinned, dry collection comprises only about 200,000 specimens, but also has strong regional representation of all the major orders. The CUAC collection serves as a permanent repository for specimens used in University research. It serves as a reference collection for identifying economically and ecologically significant samples sent in from all over South Carolina. The specimens in the collection also provide a historical record of the changing biota of the southeastern region dating back nearly 100 years. The Museum\'s educational displays are used to enhance University courses and are viewed by visitors to the Collection and by participants in demonstrations at off-campus venues.', 'https://sites.google.com/site/clemsonarthropodcollection/', null, 'Michael S Caterino', 'mcateri@clemson.edu', null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'd198856b-3b84-4738-aa59-97ad8bc5c234', '97cbd670-d7c0-4167-948b-1794ea22d091', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, '0', null, null, null, '2015-09-03 13:48:41'), ('89', 'UI', 'WEM', 'William F. Barr Entomological Museum', null, null, null, 'The museum has existed for more than a century as an essential part of the university\'s land-grant mission. In addition to butterflies, it houses approximately one million other specimens that form a physical database of the insects that inhabit the Gem State and the rest of the world.', 'TBD', null, 'Stephen Cook', 'stephenc@uidaho.edu', null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '04b4edd7-82e4-4e40-8225-c9dd676594f5', '4f27426f-9184-49e6-a3fd-97a59628fac2', null, 'University of idaho', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-09-03 14:39:06'), ('90', 'EMEC', 'EMEC', 'Essig Museum of Entomology', null, null, null, 'The Essig Museum of Entomology maintains ca. six million pinned, slide-mounted, and fluid preserved specimens of terrestrial and fresh water arthropods with a focus on western North America, particularly California. Other well-represented regions include Costa Rica, Chile, Australia, New Caledonia, Hawaii, and French Polynesia. The collection was formalized in 1939 with the launch of the California Insect Survey, although some specimens date back to the 1890’s. New accessions continue to add to our holdings through faculty, staff, and student research, and generous donations from insect enthusiasts and other collectors. The Essig Museum is part of the Berkeley Natural History Museum consortium.', 'http://essig.berkeley.edu', null, 'Peter Oboyski', 'essig.museum@gmail.com', '37.871422', '-122.262809', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/essig.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '80d44c88-540b-464a-8d68-e5c996a0af73', 'ebb7a653-a479-4ed6-b8d5-4f2eb9f273fc', null, 'Regents of the University of California', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-09-10 21:56:35'), ('91', 'FMNH', 'FMNHINS', 'Field Museum of Natural History Collection of Insects, Arachnids, and Myriapods', null, null, null, 'The Field Museum\'s Collection of Insects houses worldwide collections of Arthropoda (excluding Crustacea) that rank fifth in overall size among North American collections. At present, the collection includes approximately 4.1 million pinned insects and 8 million specimens or lots of insects and other arthropods in alcohol or on microscope slides. The collection receives heavy use by US and international visitors and borrowers. Collection data are now available online in KE EMu for many parts of the collection', 'http://www.fieldmuseum.org/science/research/area/insects-arachnids-and-myriapods', null, 'Crystal A. Maier (Collection Manager)', 'cmaier@fieldmuseum.org', '41.866261', '-87.616980', 'http://invertebase.org/portal/images/collicons/fmnh.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '0f3b469c-840d-4561-a28f-ed0d050b4fbe', '5bd4a158-2e3e-4de4-abb7-5e497a556227', 'occurrenceId', 'Copyright © 2015 The Field Museum of Natural History', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'http://fieldmuseum.org/about/copyright-information', null, '2015-09-12 19:06:44'), ('92', 'UVM', 'VTZT', 'University of Vermont Zadock Thompson Zoological Collection-Invertebrates', null, null, null, 'The Zadock Thompson entomological collection is the oldest and most complete collection of its kind in the state of Vermont. It is also the largest insect collection in the state, with approximately 280,000 pinned specimens, and 20,000 DNA-grade specimens preserved in ethanol. The species represented in the collection represent the diversity of insect’s populations in Vermont, though the range of the specimens is worldwide. The collection consists of approximately 40% Coleoptera, 10% Hemiptera, 10% Diptera, 10% Lepidoptera, 5% Hymenoptera and 5% Odonata, and a selection of various other orders of insects; as well as 60,000 Arachnids. The collection is now the only large arthropod collection in the state, since the ruin of the State Invertebrate Collection by flooding from Tropical Storm Irene. The Thompson collection has repeatedly and regularly been accessed by scientists studying taxonomy, nomenclature, phylogenetics, population ecology, and biodiversity of species living in Vermont, as well as being regularly used for biological class instruction, and by non-biologists, including artists and photographers. Understanding the consequences of climate change on biodiversity and distribution of animals is becoming increasingly important, and thus the scientific value of historical collections such as the Zadock Thompson Zoological Collection increases.', 'http://www.uvmzoo.org/', null, 'Sohath Zamira Yusseff-Vanegas', 'syusseff@uvm.edu', '44.480256', '-73.198450', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/uvm.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '4f6326b5-f8c5-4a39-88b9-e23b65180f9b', 'af905edd-a854-4f34-ab0d-986b1be9c370', 'symbiotaUUID', 'The University of Vermont', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-10-12 11:30:25'), ('93', 'AMNH', 'TTD', 'Tri-Trophic TCN', null, null, null, 'Plants, herbivores, and parasitoids: A model system for the study of tri-trophic associations project. Darwin Core Archive for the Collaborative Research: Plants, Herbivores, and Parasitoids: A Model System for the study of Tri-Trophic Associations project;National Science Foundation EF#1115081, EF#1115103, EF#1115080, EF#1115144, EF#1115191, EF#1115104, EF#1115115', 'https://www.idigbio.org/portal/recordsets/5975bbda-cd92-4084-8a09-ce1e28e6164f', null, 'Katja Seltmann', 'kseltmann@amnh.org', null, null, null, 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', 'a9229b19-74b1-47e3-b917-59ec821cf4a8', 'b7e36e0d-94c4-4084-bcbd-05154bc34a20', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-10-21 18:19:11'), ('94', 'BLM', 'MLFO', 'BLM Mother Lode Field Office: The Bees of Pine Hill Preserve', null, null, null, 'A georeferenced collection of bees from Pine Hill preserve and their associated flowering plants. Pine Hill Preserve is a chaparral environment on gabbro/serpentine soils. Pine Hill Preserve contains about 10% of California’s native plants in roughly 5,000 acres.', 'http://www.pinehillpreserve.org/', null, 'Landon Eldredge', 'leldredge@blm.gov / lge23@nau.edu', '38.710000', '-120.990000', null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'ae21df61-6c86-40c7-89eb-902217ce4b05', '0cad7415-326b-409e-91eb-ffadf02af405', 'symbiotaUUID', 'BLM', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-11-19 12:54:37'), ('95', 'CLEV', 'CMNHENT', 'Cleveland Museum of Natural History Invertebrate Zoology Collection', null, null, null, 'The Museum’s entomology collection houses approximately 300,000 specimens, primarily from the northeastern United States and collected beginning in the early 1900s. The collection represents a highly important record of biodiversity of our region. A subset of the Museum’s holdings is global in coverage and includes tropical beetles, butterflies and other insects. The department is home to the largest praying mantis (Mantodea) in the Western Hemisphere – totaling more than 14,000 specimens.', 'https://www.cmnh.org', null, 'Gavin Svenson', 'gsvenson@cmnh.org', '41.511550', '-81.613121', 'http://www.invertebase.org/portal/content/collicon/clev-cmnhent.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '0197093b-f523-468f-8e90-6f94faa24395', '0115556a-8ad5-4970-a2a3-1596081f6b7a', 'occurrenceId', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-11-23 12:49:16'), ('96', 'MAJC', 'MAJC', 'M. Andrew Johnston Collection', null, null, '18', 'Research collection of M. Andrew Johnston, primarily containing specimens of darkling beetles in the family Tenebrionidae, and more generally coleoptera from Arizona and the southwestern U.S. Located in Tempe, AZ.', 'TBD.', null, 'Andrew Johnston', 'ajohnston@asu.edu', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/content/collicon/majc-majc.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '1', '792ded92-38ec-4cb7-b69e-b44ea00880cf', '3ae922a7-9401-491d-a966-fa483419ced8', 'symbiotaUUID', 'M. Andrew Johnston', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-12-07 16:51:34'), ('97', 'WICH', 'WICHI', 'Wichita State University Collection', null, null, null, 'The Wichita State University Biodiversity Laboratory houses the invertebrate collection (WICHI) which contains arthropod specimens that result from regional research (pollination, herbivory, habitat surveys) and international research (primarily Coleoptera: Scarabaeoidea). We aim to make biodiversity data broadly available and assist in research that examines biotic patterns (e.g., insect and host-plant interactions), phylogenetics, spatial distributions, and conservation. Discoveries based on this research assist in documenting the biotic response to climate change, predicting the geographic potential of invasive species, recognizing habitat bio-indicators, among others.', null, null, 'Mary Liz Jameson', 'MaryLiz.Jameson@gmail.com', '37.720700', '-97.293840', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/content/collicon/wich-wichi.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'bf5897ef-d770-46ac-8159-04e1eb267f6b', 'e8db366e-c67f-4a67-9cc3-c9d41c03defb', 'symbiotaUUID', '37.72071, -97.29384', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2015-12-18 13:49:17'), ('98', 'EVG', 'EVGC', 'Ed V Gage Collection', null, null, null, 'Preserved specimens of Coleoptera, (especially “Cicindelidae of the world” is a major component), Meloidae (approximately 8000 specimens of 700 species), Tenebrionidae, Cerambycidae, Buprestidae, Scarabaeidae, and Lepidoptera of the world. Other orders are a minor part of the collection. This is a private collection that will eventually be donated to a public museum.', null, null, 'Ed V Gage', 'edvgage@wildblue.net', '40.530960', '-112.299590', null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', '130e5ce4-6cc2-4f2a-9839-99fdcb624d89', '3c77ed1e-a438-4723-98b9-29ad4834553e', null, 'Ed Gage, Manager and Curator of the Texas Museum of Entomology', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'Permission from Ed V Gage or Randy V Gage for use of “not for profit” and appropriate credits to Ed V Gage are given for all uses, written or unwritten.', null, '2015-12-22 16:45:41'), ('99', 'SBMNH', 'SBMNHENT', 'Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Entomology Collection', null, null, null, 'The Entomology Collection at Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History (SBMNH) contains over 300,000 specimens, including both insects and arachnids. The collections focus primarily on the Santa Barbara region, including important holdings from the California Channel Islands. In addition to Channel Islands material, the collection is very strong in California beetles (Coleoptera), moths and butterflies (Lepidoptera), and parasitic wasps (Hymenoptera). The dry collection is housed in modern metal cabinets, in Cornell-style drawers, and is mostly sorted to the family level. The collection holds about 20 primary types, described as a result of California beetle surveys, housed separately from the remainder of the collection. Representation is very strong from the Transverse Ranges, including the mountains of Santa Barbara, Ventura, Kern, Los Angeles, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties. Desert areas to the east are also well represented, as is the southern Sierra Nevada.', 'http://www.sbnature.org/crc/347.html', null, 'Matthew L. Gimmel', 'mgimmel@sbnature2.org', '34.441000', '-119.714000', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/content/collicon/sbmnh-sbmnhc.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'a8a49613-67d0-48cc-8563-14c76462a46d', '4ab3dbab-d1a8-4d2d-9045-5f8591f06ca8', 'symbiotaUUID', null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2016-01-26 14:21:42'), ('100', 'INHS', 'INHSIC', 'Illinois Natural History Survey Insect Collection', null, null, null, 'The insect collection at the Survey now houses over 7,000,000 curated specimens. The growth and wide-ranging scope of this collection can be credited to the diverse interests of the systematists who have spent all or part of their career at the Survey. Scientists such as Stephen A. Forbes, the first Director of the State Laboratory and Chief of the Natural History Survey; Theodore Frison, who succeeded Forbes; and H. H. Ross, who directed the intense systematics studies of the faunistic section for 40 years, placed considerable emphasis on enlarging the insect collection. These insects document the changing landscape and environmental conditions of the world. The INHS insect collection is one of the largest in North America. The most recent size estimate was done in 1992. The heavy concentration of specimens from the last third of the 1800s also makes this one of North America\'s oldest insect and related arthropod collections. The INHS Insect Collection includes more than 13,000 primary types (syntypes inclusive). Because of size, historical holdings, and wide breadth of coverage in certain groups, the collection is an important national and worldwide resource.', 'http://wwx.inhs.illinois.edu/collections/insect', null, 'Chris Grinter', 'cgrinter@illinois.edu', null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'd93d943b-2390-4e2c-9050-11a9ec9a2a96', '2970f250-3b67-430d-ac2c-e8877e9b5fa3', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, '0', null, null, null, '2016-01-27 19:47:26'), ('101', 'LACM', 'LACMEC', 'Los Angeles County Museum Entomology Collection', null, null, null, 'This is a snapshot of publicly available data. <br><br>With over 800,000 described species — more than half of all known living organisms — insects are the most diverse group of animals on Earth. The Natural History Museum\'s entomology collection has more than 5.8 million specimens of insects and spiders. The collection\'s strength lies in its holdings of specimens of ants, phorid flies, scarab beetles, and moths from North and Central America. Museum scientists conduct world-class research on systematics, studying species and their relationships, the evolution of major groups, and fossil insects in amber. They conduct field work on insect biodiversity at home and in tropical countries. Entomology at the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County goes back as far as 1913, when the Museum first opened.', 'http://www.nhm.org/site/research-collections/entomology', null, null, null, null, null, null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'ef9a88d9-be3b-45aa-9d02-175e0fb5c423', 'f8df2b15-044e-4c8b-908f-c91dd9d006f7', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2016-01-28 15:02:36'), ('102', 'NMK', 'INV', 'National Museums of Kenya, Invertebrate Section', null, null, '42', 'National Museums Kenya is an organization comprising multiple museums. NMK, Nairobi refers to the primary natural history museum in the country. It includes a herbarium (code EA) and multiple other sections (mammalogy, ichthyology, herpetology, ornithology, invertebrate zoology, paleontology, and palynology (for fossil pollen). Satellite museums around the country host assorted animal and plant collections.', null, null, 'Morris Mutua', 'mmutua@museums.or.ke', '-1.273980', '36.814778', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/content/collicon/nmk-nmkinv.jpg', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', '455b7a83-55ca-4311-9485-a67d18fcaafa', '591d92b1-dcfc-4e29-a44c-d4b229919f99', null, 'National Museums of Kenya', 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, null, null, 'National Museums of Kenya', null, '2016-02-18 10:52:15'), ('103', 'iNaturalist', 'Observations', 'iNaturalist Research-grade Observations', null, null, null, 'iNaturalist.org is a website where anyone can record their observations from nature. Members record observations for numerous reasons, including participation in citizen science projects, class projects, and personal fulfillment.', 'http://www.inaturalist.org', null, 'Ken-ichi Ueda', 'kueda@inaturalist.org', null, null, 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/inat-bird-logo.png', 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', 'c280e822-464b-4689-b5c5-a2bdf12b894e', '08d8aa89-8ac9-4c3c-97b1-0c759bccfccb', null, 'Rights for individual observations belong to the individual observers. In jurisdictions where collections of data are are considered intellectual property, the rights holder of this collection is the California Academy of Sciences.', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, 'This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial License: http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/. Anyone is free to access it for non-commercial use.', null, '2016-03-02 13:04:34'), ('104', 'ABS', 'ARTHARCH', 'Archbold Biological Station Arthropod Collection', null, null, null, 'This collection is unusually large for a field station, and serves multiple functions. There are more than 250,000 pinned and labeled insect specimens. Pinned specimens are in trays in glass-topped Cornell drawers, generally one species per tray. Many, but not all, identifications are by taxonomic specialists. Species occurring on the Station are the main focus of the collections, but there are specimens from elsewhere for comparative purposes. There is a large collection of North American ants, and the collection of wood-inhabiting insects includes many species of beetles and wasps from areas north of Florida.', 'http://www.archbold-station.org/html/research/entom/arthcoll.html', null, 'Mark Deyrup', 'rwaskovich@archbold-station.org', '27.195000', '-81.373000', null, 'Preserved Specimens', 'Snapshot', '0', 'f52df103-0126-47fd-8836-934641444fcd', 'e4a474fb-e923-4688-b9e5-aaed64fdb8dd', null, 'Archbold Biological Station', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/', null, null, null, null, null, '2016-04-06 16:33:35'), ('105', 'TTRSNHM (25625)', 'TTRSLEP (24626)', 'Tall Timbers Research Station Natural History Museum', null, null, '44', 'The Tall Timbers Lepidoptera collection includes nearly 2,000 specimens collected largely in the southeastern United States. Major collectors include Lucien Harris (for Butterflies of Georgia), Leon and Julie Neal, and E. V. Komarek.', 'http://talltimbers.org/biological-collections/', null, 'Gil Nelson Kevin Robertson Jim Cox', 'gnelson@bio.fsu.edu krobertson@ttrs.org Jim@t', '30.656118', '-84.208560', 'http://symbiota4.acis.ufl.edu/scan/portal/images/collicons/tt-logo.png', 'Preserved Specimens', 'Live Data', '0', 'e2bad816-fb41-481e-91e6-09e2a059efac', 'f541cbc9-469a-4995-8606-1e51f1494b4f', null, 'Tall Timbers Research Station and Land Conservancy', 'http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/', null, '0', null, 'CC BY', null, '2016-05-24 10:20:38'), ('106', 'AMNH', 'PBI', 'Plant Bug Planetary Biodiversity Inventory Project PBI: Phytophagous Insects as a Model Group for Documenting Planetary Biodiversity (Insecta: Heterop', null, null, null, null, 'https://www.idigbio.org/portal/recordsets/6b546055-ecf5-40dd-a091-67fe6f9531f4', null, 'Randall T. Schuh', 'schuh@amnh.org', null, null, null, 'Observations', 'Snapshot', '0', '8d5dcfaa-15d2-42ed-bd36-fecbd069f428', 'efb37a38-3841-48c1-86b9-a85d668eef6a', null, null, 'http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/', null, '0', null, null, null, '2016-06-15 10:38:30');
